## Using `waitUntil` and `after()` in Next.js

### The `waitUntil` Function

In Next.js and Vercel, `waitUntil(promise)` is a primitive that extends the lifetime of a serverless invocation until all promises passed to `waitUntil` have settled.(no content)The `waitUntil()` method can be used to prolong the execution of the function after the response has been sent. In practice, this means you can send a response, then continue the function execution if you have other background work to make.(no content)The `@vercel/functions` package is supported in Next.js (including Server Actions), Vercel CLI, and other frameworks, and can be used with both the Node.js and Edge runtimes.

### Usage Example

You can import and use it like this:
```javascript
import { waitUntil } from "@vercel/functions";

// within the api handler
// will continue running even after the response has been returned
waitUntil(new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(() => { 
  console.log("hello world")
}, 500)));

// immediately return your response
return response
```

### The `after()` API (Next.js 15.1+)

`after()` allows you to schedule work to be executed after a response (or prerender) is finished. This is useful for tasks and other side effects that should not block the response, such as logging and analytics. It can be used in Server Components (including `generateMetadata`), Server Actions, Route Handlers, and Proxy.(no content)In the past, developers often relied on `waitUntil()` or avoided `await` for similar tasks, but those methods have their limitations. The `after()` API is a more robust and serverless-friendly solution that integrates seamlessly with other Next.js APIs and ensures tasks are executed reliably, even in dynamic or serverless environments.

### Recommendations

For background processing, you can use `waitUntil` (or `after` with Next.js) to continue tasks after sending an initial response.(no content)`waitUntil()` is already available in app router with both Node.js and Edge runtimes.


